title = "Running nginx on all ports"
date = "2017-05-03"
type = "post"
author = "antitree"
+++

I recently came across a reason that I wanted to run an arbitrary service across all 65535 TCP ports.
If you do too, and you're like me that you don't care about it working in production,
here are some hints to make it work:

## Linux Ulimits

Check current ulimitsi, hard limits, and soft limits on your current account:
`ulimit -n`
`ulimit -Hn`
`ulimit -Sn`

To check them for the "www-data" user:
`sudo su -s /bin/bash www-data`

[This gist](https://gist.github.com/joewiz/4c39c9d061cf608cb62b) has a pretty good summary of
possible nginx configuration options you want to choose. 

* add `fs.file-max = 999999` to /etc/sysctl.conf`
* add `www-data soft nofile 999999` and `www-data hard nofile 999999` in /etc/security/limits.conf
* run sysctl -p
* add `worker_rlimit_nofile 999999;` in /etc/nginx/nginx.conf`

## Listen on all ports

Replace the listening on port 80 and add all of the ports to the /etc/nginx/sites-available/default. A
few ports are missing from the host I was running it on.
